 pk pl pm gm pn po pp pq hi bh" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">Now every bo=
ok in our dataset is a point in space. <strong class=3D"pa il">And now we u=
se a mathematical concept called Cosine Similarity. </strong>Let=E2=80=99s =
suppose we draw a straight line from the center of the grid to every book. =
Think of arrows drawn to every book. Books with similar metadata will have =
arrows pointing in the exact same direction. <strong class=3D"pa il">The sm=
aller the angle between two arrows, the more similar the books are.</strong=
></p><p id=3D"d5a6" class=3D"pw-post-body-paragraph oy oz ik pa b je pb pc =
pd jh pe pf pg gg ph pi pj gj pk pl pm gm pn po pp pq hi bh" data-selectabl=
e-paragraph=3D"">A cosine similarity ranges between 0 and 1. A score of 1 m=
eans they are identical, and a score of 0 means they have nothing in common=
.</p><h3 id=3D"2e67" class=3D"rf qc ik bc qd ga rg gb gc gd rh ge gf gg ri =
gh gi gj rj gk gl gm rk gn go rl bh" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">3. The =
Strict Threshold</h3><p id=3D"b851" class=3D"pw-post-body-paragraph oy oz i=
k pa b je qv pc pd jh qw pf pg gg qx pi pj gj qy pl pm gm qz po pp pq hi bh=
" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">The problem with most basic recommendation=
 engines is that if you ask for the 5 most similar books, they will return =
5 books, even if the 5th is a really poor match.</p><p id=3D"02dc" class=3D=
"pw-post-body-paragraph oy oz ik pa b je pb pc pd jh pe pf pg gg ph pi pj g=
j pk pl pm gm pn po pp pq hi bh" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">To fix this=
, I have set up a <strong class=3D"pa il">75% similarity threshold</strong>=
. I wanted the engine to be sensible. <em class=3D"pr">So the system will r=
ecommend books that are over 75% similarity.</em></p><h3 id=3D"0304" class=
=3D"rf qc ik bc qd ga rg gb gc gd rh ge gf gg ri gh gi gj rj gk gl gm rk gn=
 go rl bh" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">4. The Fallback &amp; Re-ranking<=
/h3><p id=3D"e79a" class=3D"pw-post-body-paragraph oy oz ik pa b je qv pc p=
d jh qw pf pg gg qx pi pj gj qy pl pm gm qz po pp pq hi bh" data-selectable=
-paragraph=3D"">But there is one edge case to be solved. What if you search=
 for a very unique book, and <em class=3D"pr">there is not a single book in=
 your database that passes the 75% threshold? </em>Getting no recommendatio=
ns is a bad experience for users.</p><p id=3D"55fc" class=3D"pw-post-body-p=
aragraph oy oz ik pa b je pb pc pd jh pe pf pg gg ph pi pj gj pk pl pm gm p=
n po pp pq hi bh" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">So, I built a smart fallba=
ck mechanism. <em class=3D"pr">If the engine is unable to find relevant mat=
ches with a score higher than 0.75, it goes to the next closest alternative=
s. </em>Yes, it fills <strong class=3D"pa il">the slots, but clearly labels=
 them in the UI as <em class=3D"pr">Alternative Match,</em> so the user is =
never misled.</strong></p><p id=3D"2bee" class=3D"pw-post-body-paragraph oy=
 oz ik pa b je pb pc pd jh pe pf pg gg ph pi pj gj pk pl pm gm pn po pp pq =
hi bh" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">Finally, if two books are equally sim=
ilar to your search, then how does the engine decide which one to recommend=
 first? For this edge case, I have added a weighted scoring system:</p><ul =
class=3D""><li id=3D"39d3" class=3D"oy oz ik pa b je pb pc pd jh pe pf pg g=
g ph pi pj gj pk pl pm gm pn po pp pq rm rn ro bh" data-selectable-paragrap=
h=3D""><strong class=3D"pa il">50%</strong> of the final score is pure simi=
larity.</li><li id=3D"3852" class=3D"oy oz ik pa b je rp pc pd jh rq pf pg =
gg rr pi pj gj rs pl pm gm rt po pp pq rm rn ro bh" data-selectable-paragra=
ph=3D""><strong class=3D"pa il">20%</strong> goes to the book=E2=80=99s Ama=
